#{\footnote whatare}${\footnote What are Nonograms?}
K{\footnote What are Nonograms?}+{\footnote Overviews:02}
\pard\keepn\f4\fs30\b What are Nonograms?\par
\pard\plain\f4\fs20
\par
\par
Nonograms are challenging puzzles which\i  are designed to test your
 powers of logic and deduction\plain\f4\fs20 . They consist of a grid
 composed of usually 500 squares (20x25). Each of these squares is either
 filled with a\b\i  block\plain\f4\fs20  (or\b\i  solid\plain\f4\fs20 ) or
 a\b\i  dot\plain\f4\fs20 . The arrangement of groups of blocks is given
 on a per row or column basis and the purpose of the puzzle is to use
 this information to determine the overall arrangement of blocks and
 dots.\par
\par
The best way of illustrating this is by an example as given in
 the \uldb quick introduction\plain\uldb\v quickintro\plain\f4\fs20
 topic.\par
\par
\par
\par\f4\fs24\b
Also see
\par\plain\f4\fs20\uldb
Contents\plain \v\f4 main_contents\plain\par \f4\fs20\uldb
About the Nonogram Solver\plain\uldb\v about\plain\uldb\f4\fs20\par
A quick introduction\plain\uldb\v quickintro\plain\uldb\f4\fs20\par
The main window\plain\uldb\v mainwindow\plain\uldb\f4\fs20\par
Program history\plain\uldb\v history\plain\uldb\f4\fs20\par
\page

#{\footnote quickintro}${\footnote A quick introduction}
K{\footnote A quick introduction}+{\footnote Overviews:03}
\pard\keepn\f4\fs30\b A quick introduction\par
\pard\plain\f4\fs20
\par\f4\fs24\b
Outline\plain\f4\fs20\par
\par
This quick introduction to the Nonogram Solver takes you through the
 stages of loading, solving and printing a Nonogram while introducing you
 to the wide selection of powerful features that the program offers.\par
\par\f4\fs24\b
Stage 1: Loading a Nonogram data file\plain\f4\fs20\par
\par
NOTE: If the Nonogram Solver is not currently running start it now by double
 clicking on the icon in Program Manager.\par
\par
To load a data file select\f4\fs18  FILE|OPEN...\f4\fs20  from the main
 menu or click on the file open tool bar button:\par
\par
\tab{\{bmc openicon.bmp\}}\par
\par
Select the file\b  CAT.NGM\plain\f4\fs20  from the list of files as shown
 below and click\b  OK\plain\f4\fs20 .\par
\par
{\{bml quick1.bmp\}}\par
\par
The file will then be loaded by the Nonogram Solver and if all is well
 the data title will appear in the status bar:\par
\par
{\{bml quick2.bmp\}}\par
\par
\par\f4\fs24\b
Stage 2: Solving a Nonogram data file\plain\f4\fs20\par
\par
To solve\i  CAT\plain\f4\fs20  select\f4\fs18  OPTIONS|SOLVE...\f4\fs20  from the main
 menu or click on the solve tool bar button:\par
\par
\tab{\{bmc solvicon.bmp\}}\par
\par
As the Nonogram is solved the display will appear as follows:\par
\par
{\{bml quick3.bmp\}}\par
\par
Note that the number of points found and time taken so far and time are
 displayed in the \uldb status bar\v statbar\plain\f4\fs20 . When the
 Nonogram has been successfully solved all the grid squares will be filled and the status bar will appear as
 follows:\par
\par
{\{bml quick4.bmp\}}\par
\par
\par\f4\fs24\b
Stage 3: Editing a Nonogram data file\plain\f4\fs20\par
\par
To edit the currently loaded Nonogram data simply click on the
 number next to the row or column of data you wish to edit as shown
 below:\par
\par
\tab{\f2\cf2 \{bmc edit1.bmp\}}\par
\par
As shown below an edit box will pop up containing the data for the row or column that
 you clicked on. You can edit this data in the normal way using any non-
 numeric character (including spaces) as a spacer between the
 numbers.\par
\par
\tab{\f2\cf2 \{bmc edit2.bmp\}}\par
\par
When you have finished editing the data press\f4\fs18  RETURN\f4\fs20
 to update it or press\f4\fs18  ESCAPE\f4\fs20  to prevent it being updated.
 If you press\f4\fs18  ESCAPE\f4\fs20  any changes you have made to the
 data will be lost. If you wish to edit the next item of data press
 the\f4\fs18  DOWN ARROW\f4\fs20  key: to edit the previous item of data
 press the\f4\fs18  UP ARROW\f4\fs20  key.\par
\par
\par\f4\fs24\b
Stage 4: Saving a Nonogram data file\plain\f4\fs20\par
\par
To save a data file select\f4\fs18  FILE|SAVE...\f4\fs20  from the main
 menu or click on the file save tool bar button:\par
\par
\tab{\{bmc saveicon.bmp\}}\par
\par
The file is automatically saved using the current file name. If the data
 has just been entered and does not have a file name or you
 select\f4\fs18  FILE|SAVE AS...\f4\fs20  from the main menu then the
 following dialog is displayed:\par
\par
{\{bml quick5.bmp\}}\par
\par
Enter a filename and then press\b  OK\plain\f4\fs20  or choose\b  Cancel\plain\f4\fs20  to cancel the operation.\par
\par
\par
