#{\footnote history}${\footnote Program history}
K{\footnote Program history}+{\footnote Overviews:05}
\pard\keepn\f4\fs30\b Program history\par
\pard\plain\f4\fs20
\par
\par
The Nonogram Solver was originally designed as a DOS based program and
 written in MicroSoft Quick Basic v4.5. Version 1.0 could handle fixed
 size (20x25) Nonograms and displayed the output data using either a
 text or VGA based approach. In terms of speed it was roughly twice as
 slow as this version. It was released on 03/02/93.\par
\par
The heart of the Nonogram solving code was then ported to Windows to
 form the basis of version 1.1 of the Nonogram Solver. The program was
 rewritten in Pascal to run under Windows v3.1 and was released on
 24/05/93. Compared to the current program version 1.1 was quite
 primitive as if had only a single non-resizable non-scrollable main
 window, could only solve fixed sized Nonograms (20x25) and was no
 faster than the DOS version due to its limited display handling.\par
\par
Version 1.2 offered increased solve times of up to 33% faster than the previous version.
 It also offered cosmetic improvements by using Borland's custom controls to draw all
 the dialog interface objects. It was released on 15/08/93.\par
\par
Version 2.0 overcame the most serious shortcoming of all the previous
 versions by allowing Nonograms sizes from 1x1 up to 100x100 to be solved
 with ease. The whole of the solving code ported from version 1.0 was
 also rewritten and tool and status bars added. It
 was released on 20/12/93.\par
\par
Version 2.1 added an extra solution option - 'Single'. This enabled it
 to solve one Nonogram that the previous versions could not,\i  Hermit
 Crab\plain\f4\fs20 . It was released on 20/02/94.\par
\par
Version, 2.2, improved upon the previous versions
 considerably. It offered full MDI functionality enabling multiple Nonogram
 display windows to be open at the same time. The screen design were
 improved with a 3D look and Borland's custom controls were
 replaced by MicroSoft's 3D controls. A new interactive editing feature
 was added allowing data to be edited insitu and then saved to disk.
 An improved data parser calculated the data complexity as well as
 checking whether the data set is consistent. A new solution option -
 'Greedy' - allowed solve times to be reduced at the cost of less
 processor time for other Windows applications. File handling has been
 improved and a new automatic installation program simplified the
 program setup. It was released on 10/04/94.\par
\par
The major new features of version 2.2 are listed below:\par
\par
\tx360\li360\fi-360
{\f1\'B7}
\tab MDI compliancy - multiple Nonograms loaded at the same time.\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab In-place entry, editing and saving of data.\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab Improved 3D look with configurable colours.\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab Data complexity calculator as well as consistancy checker.\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab Automatic installation program.\par
\pard
\par
Version 2.21 added a few minor changes in how the Nonogram Solver handles
 screen display of data and improved the in place editing functions.
 It was released on 02/05/94.\par
\par
Version 2.3, the current version, offers a revised interface and
 slightly improved solution times. It was released on 15/11/94.\par
\par
\par
