#{\footnote opendata}${\footnote Open a data file}
K{\footnote Open a data file}+{\footnote Howto:03}
\pard\keepn\f4\fs30\b Open a data file\par
\pard\plain\f4\fs20
\par
\par
You can open a data file by either selecting\f4\fs18  FILE|OPEN\f4\fs20  from the main
 menu as shown below:\par
\par
{\f2\cf2 \{bmc openmenu.bmp\}}\par
\par
or by clicking on the open tool bar button:\par
\par
\tab{\f2\cf2 \{bmc openicon.bmp\}}\par
\par
After you have selected a file name the file will be loaded into the
 currently active display window. If there are no display windows
 currently open a new display window will be created and the data loaded
 into it.\par
\par
Various errors can occur when loading a data file. The Nonogram Solver
 automatically checks a data file for errors as it is loading it and
 displays an error message if the file is found to be corrupted. A list
 of the error messages follows along with typical reasons as to why they
 are displayed.\par
\par
\tx360\li360\fi-360
{\f1\'B7}
\tab {\b <File name>: No title specified.}\par
\par
\tab This error is displayed if the title field of the data file is
 blank.\par
\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab {\b <File Name>: Data file is corrupt:  Invalid Nonogram size specified.}\par
\par
\tab This error is displayed if a Nonogram size smaller than 1x1 or
 greater than 100x100 is specified. The file will not be loaded if this message is displayed.\par
\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab {\b <File Name>: Data file is corrupt:  Line entry truncated.}\par
\par
\tab This message is displayed if a line of data has more than 30
 elements specified.\par
\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab {\b <File Name>: Data file is corrupt:  Data missing.}\par
\par
\tab This message is displayed if the amount of data supplied does not
 correspond to the Nonogram size given earlier in the data file.\par
\par
{\f1\'B7}
\tab {\b <File Name>: Data cannot be solved: Use the Information menu option for more help.}\par
\par
\tab This message is displayed if the data is not consistent and fails
 the parse test. See the \uldb data information\v datainfo\plain\f4\fs20  topic for more information.\par
\pard
\par
More information on the data file format is contained in the \uldb save
 a data file\v savedata\plain\f4\fs20  topic.\par
\par
\par
