\page

#{\footnote pd_area2}
{\f4\fs24\b Grid size}\plain\f4\fs20\par
\par
The size of the Nonogram data in the active window is displayed here. These values can be
 edited in the \uldb data header\v datahead\plain\f4\fs20  dialog. 
\page

#{\footnote pd_area3}
{\f4\fs24\b Parse check}\f4\fs20\par
\par
The two numbers here reflect the result of the data consistency parse
 check. They are the sum of all the elements for the X and Y directions
 and if the data is consistent the numbers should be the same. If they
 are not then the data cannot be solved.
\page

#{\footnote pd_area4}
{\f4\fs24\b File information}\f4\fs20\par
\par
If the data in the active window has been loaded from a saved data file
 the date and size of the file are displayed here.
\page

#{\footnote pd_area5}
{\f4\fs24\b Comments}\f4\fs20\par
\par
The comment displayed here reflects whether the data passed the
 consistency parse check.
\page

#{\footnote pd_area6}
{\f4\fs24\b Average row combinations}\f4\fs20\par
\par
The number displayed here is a single cell average combination number generated by
 the complexity calculator.\par
\par
The latter examines each row and column in turn and calculates the maximum number
 of ways that the data in that row can be arranged. It then divides the
 number obtained by the number of cells in that row (typically 20 or 25)
 to arrive at the\b  average\plain\f4\fs20  value displayed here. The\b  total\plain\f4\fs20  value
 is the sum of the all the number of combinations for each row and
 column and is included purely for reference.
\page

#{\footnote pd_area7}
{\f4\fs24\b Data complexity level}\f4\fs20\par
\par
The comment displayed here is determined by the value of the \ul average row
 combinations\v pd_area6\plain\f4\fs20 .
\page

