#{\footnote sd_area1}
{\f4\fs24\b Quick start}\f4\fs20\par
\par
Select this check box to enable the\b  quick start\plain\f4\fs20  algorithm.\par
\par
This algorithm, as suggested by the name speeds up the rate at which the solution initially
 progresses. It essentially looks for 'safe bets' in the data (eg rows which can only be
 arranged in one way) and fills them in.\par
\par
It should be noted that this algorithm, if enabled, is only used once at the start of a
 solution run.
\page

#{\footnote sd_area2}
{\f4\fs24\b Edge checking}\f4\fs20\par
\par
Select this check box to enable the\b  edge checking\plain\f4\fs20  algorithm.\par
\par
This algorithm is designed to accelerate the starting speed of the solution. In this case
 only the outer rim of the puzzle is scanned. If a fully filled square is found in any
 of these positions it is extended by the amount given in the puzzle data set.\par
\par
In general this algorithm does not significantly decrease the time taken to find a solution.
\page

#{\footnote sd_area3}
{\f4\fs24\b Full row testing}\f4\fs20\par
\par
Select this check box to enable the\b  full row testing\plain\f4\fs20  algorithm.\par
\par
This checks for full rows and if it finds one marks it as such, so that no other algorithm
 tries to check it in future. It can speed up the solution time noticeably, particularly if
 used with the combinational algorithm.
\page

#{\footnote sd_area4}
{\f4\fs24\b Row following}\f4\fs20\par
\par
Select this check box to enable the\b  row following\plain\f4\fs20  algorithm.\par
\par
This method starts at the beginning of a row or column and tries to work across to the
 other end, using the puzzle data. Can be useful depending on the puzzle.
\page

#{\footnote sd_area5}
{\f4\fs24\b Single}\f4\fs20\par
\par
Select this check box to enable the\b  single\plain\f4\fs20  algorithm.\par
\par
The single algorithm is designed to deal with rows or columns of data
 with only one element size. If it finds an element in such a row it can
 safely position a dot at either end of the element. The advantage of
 this method is that while such situations can theoretically be solved by
 brute force using the \ul combinational\v sd_area6\plain\f4\fs20
 algorithm this algorithm produces a solution much more rapidly. In many
 cases such a row of length 25 with 7 blocks of unity length (50388
 possible combinations) the \uldb VARS\v sd_area8\plain\f4\fs20  array is
 exhausted long before all the allowable combinations have been tested.
\page

#{\footnote sd_area6}
{\f4\fs24\b Combinational}\f4\fs20\par
\par
Select this check box to enable the\b  combinational\plain\f4\fs20  algorithm.\par
\par
This is the most important algorithm. Basically it calculates the number of ways in which
 the available data can be arranged into any particular row or column. It discounts any
 solutions which disagree with the data already present and temporarily stores any solutions
 which appear to fit. It then examines all these solutions looking for matching data, before
 updating the grid with any new data it has found.\par
\par
How many potential solutions it can store before giving up (it will give up and move to
 the next line if it finds more potential solutions than it can store) depends on the
 setting of \uldb VARS\v sd_area8\plain\f4\fs20 . The default value is 300, but this can be increased
 to 600. Obviously this will increase the computational time, and a value greater than twenty
 is usually only required if the combinational algorithm is being used on its own.
\page

#{\footnote sd_area7}
{\f4\fs24\b Greedy mode}\f4\fs20\par
\par
Select this check box to enable\b  greedy mode\plain\f4\fs20  operation.\par
\par
When greedy mode is enabled the Nonogram Solver allocates more processor
 time to itself and less to other applications reducing the time taken to
 find a solution.\par
\page

#{\footnote sd_area8}${\footnote VARS}K{\footnote VARS}
\pard\keepn\f4\fs30\b VARS\par
\pard\plain\f4\fs20
\par
\par
The size of the VARS array can be modified using this edit control. It
 has an allowable range of 1 to 600.\par
\par
This array is used in conjunction with the combinational algorithm and has a default value
 of 300. In all cases this is sufficient to solve all the supplied Nonograms.\par
\par
\b\f4\fs20 Typical solution times using v1.1a\par
\par
\plain \i\f4\fs20
\par
\tab VARS \tab  Time  \tab  Successful\par
\par \plain \f4\fs20
\tab 5 \tab  0.3 \tab NO\par
\tab 10 \tab 15.8 \tab YES\par
\tab 20 \tab 12.7 \tab YES\par
\tab 50 \tab 13.9 \tab YES\par
\tab 100 \tab 14.2 \tab YES\par
\par
\b\f4\fs20 Typical solution times using v2.3\par
\par
\plain \i\f4\fs20
\par
\tab VARS \tab  Time  \tab  Successful\par
\par \plain \f4\fs20
\tab 5 \tab  0.2 \tab NO\par
\tab 10 \tab 11.3 \tab YES\par
\tab 20 \tab 9.2 \tab YES\par
\tab 50 \tab 10.0 \tab YES\par
\tab 100 \tab 10.2 \tab YES\par
\par
NOTE: These results were obtained using GEMINI.NGM on a 486SX25 PC.
\par
\par
It should also be borne in mind that the best solution time obtained using v2.3 to solve
GEMINI.NGM was 4.4 seconds. This was obtained by setting the VARS size to 20 and turning
